WINE QUALITY by Pratik Asarkar

This report explores a dataset containing the quality and physicochemical properties of red wine for approximately 1600 observations.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 observations of wine in the dataset with 13 variables(X, fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol,quality). All the variables are numeric type except for quality which is of type int.

Other observations: 1. For most of the wines the quality lies between 5 and 7. 2. The mean alcohol percentage is 10.42 %.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features in the dataset are alcohol percentage in wine and quality of wine. Also other variables that attracted my attention are pH values and fixed/volatile acidity to check to acidic content of red wines.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

volatile acidity, citric acid, total sulfur dioxide and density are other attributes which I think contribute to the quality of wine. Alcohol contributes the most to the quality of alcohol as far as other attributes are compared.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No. I did not create any new variable from the existing variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Citric acid had an unusual distribution as showed 3 modes in its plot.Also volatile acidity seems to be bimodal with its dip near the mean and median. There seems to a positive skewness in sulphates histogram, so I transformed it to log10. The transformed histogram gave a more normal distribution. Similarly total and free sulfur dioxide are positively skewed hence we can use log transformation to get them to normal distribution.

Most wines with quality 7 have high sulphates concentration.

Red wine of quality 5 has fixed acidity between 6 - 12 and is most dense close to 7 and 8. There are more number of redwines with quality of 6 and 6 but the wines with quality 6 seems to be more spread out in the region.

We can see clear positive correlation between total sulfur dioxide and free sulfur dioxide for redwine.

Minimum pH value for redwine is close to 3.0-3.1 and most of them near ph value 3.0 are quality 5 redwines.

In this plot we can notice that most of red wine is clustered around where citric acid is 0 - 0.5 and most of them have been rated with quaity of 5 or 6.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One: Quality of Wine

Description One

We may say that most frequent quality levels are 5 and 6 for the red wine. The main reason for this plot is that it gives us the overall trends of the quality of red wine. We can also see that the good quality wines and bad quality wines are very less in quantity. This could be due to the bais in the rating of the wines depending upon how many people have rated the wine.

Plot Two

Description Two

Density and Alcohol show one of the strongest correlations among all wine parameters and it equals to -0.496. We can see that as the alcohol concentration decreases the density increases thus showing an obvious relationship between alcohol and density. The reason for choosing this plot as one of the finals is that it shows us the dependency of density on alcohol. As density is a factor which could affect the quality of wine, alcohol is also indirectly related with the quality of wine. There could also be a fact that the person who rates the wine finds the alcohol content most specific for a feature to be considered.

Plot Three

Description Three

We can also see that there is a strong correlation between ph and fixed acidity. It has the strongest correlation coefficient of -0.683 among all the other feature available in the dataset. The reason to highlight this plot is to show how increase in the acidity decrease the pH value of a solution. Being non volatile, it does not release any odour which might not have influenced the quality of wine.

Reflection

Analyzing the data we can come up the following conclusion:

When alcohol percentage decreases, density grows. When fixed acidity increases density of red wine increases as well. Wine with high alcohol percentage has quality level 7, wine with less alcohol percentage is quality level 5. Mostly frequent quality levels of red wine are 5 and 6.

The most challenging part of this analysis was to try and find a relationship between variables depending on their correlation as there aren’t many strong relationships in this analysis. The strongest corrletion was between pH and fixed acidity with coefficient of -.683. So trying to find the factors influencing the quality of wine was most challenging.

The analysis has alcohol as a factor which I was able to successfully find which could infulence the quality of red wine as shown in final plot 2. Also the volatile acidity against quality boxplot shows us a relationship as volatile acidity decreases quality increases. This means high level of acetic acid leads to unpleasant, vinegar taste which influences the quality of alcohol.

According to my investigation I may conclude that experts’ decisions on wine quality levels are based on their personal tests or could depend on other variables like year of production, grape types, wine brand etc. as only one or two variables (alcohol level and sulphates) have correlation with quality of wine.

So the question for future work could be that are the features mentioned in this dataset sufficient for finding the factors influencing the quality of wine, or could there be more?
